Wesnoth Unit Finder
A C++ utility designed to recursively parse and index Wesnoth Markup Language (WML) configuration files. This project demonstrates a custom, systems-level implementation of a Hash Table using manual memory management and collision handling.

Features
Custom WML Parsing: Uses std::filesystem to recursively navigate directory structures and std::stringstream to extract unit attributes such as Level, Cost, and Usage.

Data Sanitization: Implements logic to handle WML-specific formatting, including the removal of braced macros (e.g., {SPECIAL_NOTES}) and stripping translation prefixes.

O(1) Search Performance: A case-insensitive command-line interface for instant unit lookups.

Manual Memory Control: Implements a low-level Hash Table using malloc and placement new for precise object lifecycle management.

Technical Implementation
1. Hash Table Architecture
Instead of using standard library containers, this project utilizes a template-based Hash Table implemented from scratch:

Hashing Algorithm: Employs the djb2 hash function for high-speed string distribution.

Collision Resolution: Utilizes Linear Probing (Open Addressing) with a custom chain_fixer logic to maintain index integrity during item removal.

Dynamic Resizing: Automatically doubles capacity and re-hashes all entries once the load factor exceeds 0.5.

2. Memory Management
The project demonstrates low-level memory handling to optimize performance:

Raw Allocation: Uses malloc for the underlying table structure to control memory alignment and allocation.

Object Lifecycle: Utilizes placement new to construct Key and Value objects only when an entry is active, paired with explicit destructor calls to prevent memory leaks.

3. Standards and Tools
C++17/20: Leverages std::filesystem::recursive_directory_iterator for efficient traversal of complex directory trees.

STL Integration: Uses std::transform and lambdas for data normalization and string manipulation.

Data Source
This project parses unit definitions from The Battle for Wesnoth.

License: Game data is licensed under GNU GPL v2.

Official Repository: Full unit files are available via the Wesnoth GitHub mirror.

Getting Started
Prerequisites
A compiler supporting C++17 or higher (GCC 8+, Clang 7+, or MSVC 19.14+).

The wesnoth/units data folder must be located in the application's working directory.

Build and Run
Clone the repository.

Navigate to the source directory.

Compile using a C++17 compliant compiler:
g++ -std=c++17 main.cpp -o UnitFinder

Execute the application:
./UnitFinder
